{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170847/1946041801/0212.xml":{"full_text":"2\nPopular Appeal and Political\nOrganization\nWidespread and competent work\nis reported in setting up a political\norganization for ex-Gov Stassen of\nMinnesota as the Republican presi\ndential nominee in 1948 against\nwhat is recognized as the strongly\nentrenched position of the conserva\ntive wing of the party, represented\nespecially by Senator Taft and ex-\nGov Bricker of Ohio.\nThirty-eight years ago it was,\nsaid of Taft's father in football,\nterms that he was a Yale man\nmaking a run for the presidency\nprotected by the Harvard inter\nference of Theodore Roosevelt. To\nday, as the conservative leader in\nthe Senate and having had one try\nas Ohio\u2019s favorite son for the nomi\nnation in 1940, Taft is furnishing\ninterference for Bricker. If Bricker\nshould be defeated next fall in his\nrun for the other Ohio senatorship,\nit w'v\u2019Md .c .\u2019lnve him from the list\nof available presidential candidates\nand leave Taft as the immediate\nbeneficiary with no further obliga\ntion to Bricker based on the past.\nThe situation revives the old and\nUnanswered question of the value\nof popular appeal as compared with i\nthat of political organization. It\nis much like that other old question\nof the comparative value of attack\nand defense both in war and in\nathletic games. Whichever wins, or\nseems to win, is the better for the\ntime being. But neither can be\nentirely separated from the other.\nWhen Mr Roosevelt was first\nnominated by the Democrats, in\n1932, his success was largely at-'\ntributed to the organization work\nwhich had been done for him\nthroughout, the country by James\nA. Farley. Mr Farley, with his\ncard index, his followup system for\nletters, and his unfailing memory\nfor names, was added to the list of\nmodern miraclemen.\nThereafter Farley grew less and\nless important. He finally was\nchiefly known as a dissenter. Mr\nRoosevelt became the first Presi\ndent to break the two-term tradi\ntion. He then went on to a fourth\nelection because of the strength of\nhis popular appeal in wartime and\nnot because of the strength of the\nDemocratic organization.\nAdditional conflicting evidence is\nfurnished by the political history of\nboth Herbert Hoover and Wendell,\nWillkie. In 1920 Mr Hoover had\ncaught the public fancy by his in-i\nvaluable services in. the cause of i\nBelgian relief and then as public\nfood administrator in World war I.\nBut he hesitated for a long time\nwhether or not to offer himself as\na presidential candidate, seemed at\nfirst not quite sure whether he was\nB Republican or a Democrat, and;\nwas put forward by zealous but po\nlitically amateurish friends.\nThe result was that in 1920 j\nHoover never got to first base, so\nfar as actual support was concerned,\nat the Chicago convention, which i\nbecame a tragic episode in our po-[\nlitical history because it nominated\nWarren G. Harding. Eight years\nlater, when Coolidge did not choose\nto run. Hoover had no strong Re\npublican opponent; his friends had l\nlearned something about the w-ays\nof political organization, and there\nwas no stopping his nomination at\nthe Kansas City convention.\nIn 1940 Wendell Willkie knocked\na good many preconceived political\nideas into a cocked hat. Moving\ninto the race for the Republican\ndomination after the primaries\nwere practically over, he upset the\nwhole situation by the combination\nof his dramatic appeal to the public,\nand by a quickly organized effort j\nin his behalf in which political\namateurs were credited at the time\nwith having taught something to\nthe most hardened professionals.\nFour years later Mr Willkies\nfailure and collapse as a candidate\nwere primarily due to tne fact that,\nalthough he still made a strong per\nsonal appeal to many Republicans,\nhe was revealed as not being, after\n*ll, a very good organizer himself\nand as not having an effective per-;\nTranent organization within the\nparty on which he could depend.\nIf Stassen is to win the Repub\nlican nomination in 1948 over\nBricker, Taft, Dewey or any late\nentrant to whom the conservatives\nmay throw their power in preference\nto Stassen, he will need both to\nmake a strong popular appeal and\nto have a strong organization be\nhind him. The conservatives seem\nto hold too many advantages for\nhim to win otherwise.\n(April Hl\nTruman and the Admirals\nPresident Truman s position inl\nregard to the army and navy\nmerger and his sharp criticism o-\n\"the admirals\u2019\u2019 for the way in which i\nthey have continued to register!\ntheir opposition since he defined his'\nown view have an importance be-'\nyond the immediate issue. It has;\na hearing on the kind of President,\nthat Harry Truman may eventually:\nturn out to be, when he has had a.\nlonger time to profit by experience.\nand mistakes in the world\u2019s most\noverburdened office, to which an j\narmy-navy merger would furnish\nsome relief at the same time that;\nit assured greater military effi\nciency.\nMr Truman's stand on this issue!\ncannot be appraised without giving\nconsideration to two facts. The first\nof these facts, referred to when his\ndecision was first announced, is\nthat it would have been easier for\nhim to avoid the prickly issue than\nis usually the case. There had been\nurgent recommendations by some\nallegedly neutral Washington ob\nservers that the time was not ripe\nfor a decision and that the matter\nshould be referred to a commission,\njust like so many other questions on\nwhich politicians like to stall. If\nMr Truman had chosen that way\nout, he would probably have met\nlittle criticism.\nThe second fact involves the per\njsonal equation. It was well known,\nwhen the President announced his\nposition, that his chief of military\n[staff and personal adviser. Admiral\n[William D. Leahy, was not in favor\n[of the merger, although Admiral\nI Leahy, with characteristic wisdom\n[and discretion, had refrained from\n[expressing himself in such terms as\n[some other naval officers have used\nboth before and since. It is clear\nthat Mr Truman, in not following\nIthe course which Admiral Leahy can\nbe assumed to have recommended\nto him, must have been moved by I\na strong conviction both that an\narmy and navy merger was wise\nand that it should be undertaken as\nsoon as possible when the experi-;\n\u25a0ences and the lessons of the war,\nwere still fresh in the public mind.\nThe almost universal estimate of\nAdmiral Leahy as one of the ablest\nnaval officers whom the United\nStates navy has produced in many\nyears adds to the impression of in\ndependent strength on Mr Truman s\nnart which is created by the episode!\nas a whole. It was well known.\nthat President Roosevelt relied upon\nAdmiral Leahy\u2019s advice to a notable\ndegree. There have been evidences!\nin other matters that he still oc-[\ncupies a position of large influence\nwith President Truman and that[\nthe President has respect for his j\njudgment, even though differing\nfrom it in this instance.\nIt has been predicted from time\n[to time by one or two mischievous\nWashington columnists that Ad\n[miral Leahy was about to fade from\n[the picture. But a year after Mr\nTruman\u2019s accession to the presi\ndency, and in contrast to all the\ncabinet changes which have taken\nplace, Admiral Leahy still occupies\nthe same position. The fact, that the\nadmiral reached the retiring age in\n1939, so far as active naval service\nwas concerned, after which he\nserved as governor-general of\nPuerto Rico and as embassador to\n[Vichy, France, would make his\nwithdrawal from his present posi\ntion at some time in the future an\nevent not necessarily possessed of\nthe significance rashly attributed\nto it by the observers who have pre\ndicted it within a period in which\nit has not happened.\n[April Hl\nThe Bailey bridge, which was de-[\nsigned to aid allied invasion forces\n[in crossing streams in wartime, is\n[to be used in another sort of war\nfare, the United States forestry\nservice having added such a span\nto its fire-fighting equipment. Such\na bridge can be thrown across a\nriver or chasm from the attacking\nside and is counted on to assist in\nmaneuvering the forces of defense\nin battles with forest fires. The\nchances are it will not let them\n[down.\nThe atom is doing things to us\nall the time in diversified ways. Sec-\u2019\nretary Byrnes\u2019s attitude immediate\nly changed regarding Poland's com\nplaint to the Security Council about\nFranco Spain as a menace to world\npeace when the Polish delegate\nhinted that Nazi refugee scientists\nin Spain are at work on an atom\nbomb. The prospect now is that\nSpain will be put on the agenda.\nSuch is the effect of the atom on\ndiplomacy in the United Nations.\nIt is a highly sensitive area that\nthe atom dominates. An American\npricks up his ears nervously in\nreading that Pravda, yesterday,\nprinted an article by a Russian\nscientist named Tam. Our secret\nis being jealously guarded. The\nUnited States is still spending\n$500,000,000 a year for the develop\nment of atomic energy and the im\nprovement of atom bombs\u2014ssoo,-\n000,000 the spending of which has\napparently escaped the attention of\nthe House appropriations commit\ntee, which has recently' warned:\u2014\nThere seems to have developed\nduring the war y ears what some\nhave termed \"a spending psychol\nogy\u201d and the committee is fearful\nthat this spending psychology has\nbecome somewhat too deeply en\ntrenched in the minds of officials\nresponsible for the operation of\nour federal establishments. It\nmust be eliminated.\nBut so long as the atom goes\nuntamed, the fabulous spending on\nit will probably continue. For 1\nsomething like a race seems to be\ndeveloping. The Polish delegate to!\nthe Security Council in effect:\ncharges Spain with having gone,\ninto the atom bomb business; and;\nI now Mr Tam, the Russian scien\ntist. writes in Pravda that Russian\nresearch under the five-year plan\n[will follow the atomic energy line\nI with ail possible zeal. Meantime,\nj the atomic energy commission of\nthe United Nations has not made a\nstart even, Mr Baruch of the United\nI States being the only member thus\nfar appointed.\nBut, slow as that commission\nmay be in starting on its mission\nto establish international control of\nthe atom, the security alarmists at\nhome are beginning to demand\nmore stringent federal espionage\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD. MASS.: THURSDAY, APRIL IR, 1946\nCharges Against \u2018('oops'\nA broad analysis of the competi\ntive relationships between coopera\ntives and other forms of private\nbusiness enterprise is provided in a\nrather unusual report on the sub\nject just issued by the select com\nmittee on small business of the na\ntional House of Representatives. It\n[has been published at the conclusion\n[of a year of investigation that led\n[the committee unanimously to re\nject the charge that cooperatives\nembody a threat to the private en\nterprise system because they enjoy\ntax exemption and other privileges\nnot enjoyed by competitors operat\ning for private profit.\nThe particular matter investi-\n[gated by the committee was the\n[alleged ability of certain coopera\nfives to amass large untaxed re\ni serves with which they might pur\nchase other business enterprises to\n[compete with taxable forms of busi\nness. The committee recognizes\nkhat there may be some grounds\n[for questioning but concludes that|\npresent legal precedent already pro-\nvides the means of deterring \"any\ngroup which attempts to abuse the\nexemption granted to true coopera\ntives.\u201d It concludes that there is\n[no evidence to indicate that the\ncooperative movement \"seriously I\nendangers\u201d other forms of business.\nTo discourage the accumulation\n[of untaxed reserves the committee!\nrecommends that the commissioner\nof internal revenue \"require that!\nall refunds due to patrons, but re\ntained as reserves by the coopera\ntives. be subject to mandatory\u2019 pay\nment at stated intervals not to ex\nceed five years.\u201d These and other\nrecommendations designed to define\na \"reasonable reserve\u201d and a \"nec\nessary purpose\u201d for its use seem\nintended to hold cooperatives to\ntheir primary purpose of operating\nat cost for their members through\ndistribution of profits to taxable\nindividuals.\nThese same members, indeed,\nespecially in the case of agricul\ntural \"coops,\u201d which are given chief\nattention in the report, presumably\n1 would be inclined, in most cases,\n[to hold their organizations to such\na course of action of their own ac\ncord. since their reason for becom\ning patron-stockholders is to re\nalize greater economies in their\npurchases and larger returns from\ntheir sales. From the standpoint\nof their interests, the committee re\nport presents a strong defense for\ntheir jointly owned and operated\nenterprises in the controversy with\nmore individualistic forms of busi\nness.\n\"As a result of the limited num\nber of cooperatives which have\nqualified for exemption of re\nserves,\u201d the committee concludes,\n\"no appreciable revenue would ac\ncrue to the government if income\ntaxes were levied on these\namounts.\u201d It seems clear to the\ncommittee, moreover, that \"non\ncooperative business agencies, if\nthey were willing to render services\nFollowing the Atom\nlaw. They got a terrible scare\nfrom the Canadian spy cases in\nwhich some Canadian and British\nscientists were charged with giving\nto Russia, then one of our own al\nlies in the war, some atom bomb\ninformation.\nThe atom, consequently, has got\nsnarled up with treason, and it is\na question where it will end. A dis\ntinguished writer in the Wall Street\nJournal declares that, regardless of\nspecific evidence, all Communist\nsympathizers, particularly the \u201cfa-\nnatical sort,\u201d \u201care potential spies\nand traitors\u201d in this atom business.\nHe suggests, therefore, as \u201can ele\nmentary national security precau\ntion,\u201d all persons of this type be ex\ncluded \u201cfrom any position in which\nthey could have access to military\nand scientific secrets.\u201d\nTreatment of any American citi\nzens that way would mean, in ef\nfect, that they were treated as trai\ntors in the absence of overt acts or\nof specific proof. Yet the constitu\ntion of the United States is very\ncareful to define treason as a crime\nconsisting \u201conly\u201d in levying war\nagainst our government, or in ad-\nhering to our declared enemies. And\n\u201cno person shall be convicted of\ntreason unless on the testimony of\ni two witnesses to the same overt\ni act, or on confession in open court.\u201d\nAt this rate, stiffening the es\npionage laws, as some demand, may\ni bring the atom and the constitution\nlof the United States into a head-on\ncollision.\n(April 121\nThe eight assistant secretaries\ngeneral of UN\u2014one from each of\n[the big five nations and one each\n[from the Netherlands, Czechoslo\nvakia and Chile, are all distin\nguished men with long careers as\ndiplomats, executives and coun\nselors. The fact is eloquent of the\nseriousness with which the nations\nare taking their union.\nThe building on the late World\u2019s\nfair grounds where the General As\n[sembly of the United Nations is to\nmeet in September is now being\nused as a skating rink. But it will\nbe merely coincidental if there is\nsome skating on thin ice there when\nthe Assembly gets under waj.\nEDITORIAL DISCUSSION\nInternational\nThe soft coal strike began April\n1, but it is no joke. In two weeks\n[the production shutdown has re\niduced the stocks in reserve nearly\nI to the level of industrial paralysis.\nThe outlook is that the shutdown\ni will continue at least two weeks\nmore, and what two weeks more\nmay do to industry must ne left to 1\nthe imagination.\nIt looks as if the government\nwere a futile reliance for the peo\nple. It was weak gnough in war\ntime when Secretary Ickes func\nttioned rather fitfully, if energetical-!\nI ly, as fuel administrator. The war[\npressure, however, did have a cer-\ntain restraining effect on Mr Lewis\u2019s I\ndemands. We owe the ineffective\nSmith-Connally act to one of the\ncoal strikes, but the President does;\nnot contemplate any resort to it. j\nInneed. it would be difficult to\nbring the present coal strike or\n[Mr Lewis\u2019s leadership under its\npunitive provisions. He has it ar-\nranged so that the miners simply\nquit work when their contract ex\npires and they\u2019 refuse to work until\n[the union gets a new one. Mr\n[Lewis does not order them this way\n[or that. The union is like a trained\ndog in going through the motions\nexpected of it. The discipline of\nthe miners\u2019 union is marvellous and\nMr Lewis is undeniably a great\nleader.\n\"\"But. in the present strike, it is\nhard to line up in support of Mr\nLewis\u2019s crucial demand, which does\nnot concern wages so much as it\ndoes the concession of a royalty of,\nperhaps. 10 cents a ton, on all coal\nproduced, to be paid by the opera\ntors into a new miners\u2019 welfare\nfund. Mr Lewis now refuses to\ntalk about wages; he insists that\nat cost, would not be subject to any\nincome tax. The cooperative\nentity serves only as an agent for\nand on behalf of its members and\nat no time does its income be\nlong to other than its members,\nIt does not appear reasonable or\nequitable to attempt to levy a tax\non a cooperative for income which\ndoes not belong to it.\u201d\n[April 13]\nBritish Evacuation of\nAlexandria\nThe British are reported to be\nleaving Alexandria, Egypt, which\nserved as their most important\nnaval base in the eastern Mediter\nranean during the war. It is not\nclear to what degree this is related\nto the larger question of the con\ntinued presence of the British in\nEgypt or to the fact that, having\nother bases which do not involve\nany political issue, they believe that\nAlexandria is not necessary.\nThe difficulty in relating the Brit\nish withdrawal from Alexandria to\nnegotiations now being carried on\nat Cairo by Sir Ronald Campbell,\nnewly arrived British embassador\nat the court of King Farouk in\nCairo, is this: On the same day that\nthe withdrawal from Alexandria\nwas frankly reported as a fact, the\ncontinuation of Alexandria as a\nBritish base, protecting the lifeline\nof the British empire, was also re\nported from Cairo to be one of the\nthings that Sir Ronald Campbell\nhoped to secure in the face of thei\nrising tide of militant Egyptian na-[\ntionalism and the demand for ai\ncomplete British evacuation.\nObviously, the dispatches from\nEgypt do not agree. But, since a\nmilitary withdrawal, once it is in\nprogress, is a physical, visible fact,\nthe dispatch stating that the British\nare \u201cdefinitely evacuating the great\nnaval instalations at Alexandria\u201d\nseems more reliable and a safer\nbasis for endeavoring to decipher\nthe British program. It is hardly\nto be supposed that the British ad\nmiralty is trying to do one thing\nwhile the British foreign office is\ntrying to do another. Such charges\nhave sometimes been made against\nour state and navy departments at\nT o Our Present Readers\nIf in these days, which seem charged with such vital\nissues at home and abroad. The Weekly Republican\nappeals to you because of the breadth and sanity of its\neditorials, the comprehensiveness of its news and the\nvaried interest of its special features, we shall appreciate\nyour aid in sending us the names and addresses of others\nto whom you believe the paper would make a similar\nappeal.\nTo all such persons we are glad to send the paper\non free trial. From them there often comes a word of\npeculiar encouragement in the publication of an independ\nent and liberal newspaper in a time when the truth is\nso much obscured by prejudice and passion and when\ndestinies which hang in the balance put so great a\npremium on calm, clear thinking. With their subscrip\ntions come inspiring little notes telling us that The Weekly\nRepublican is the paper for which they have long been\nlooking.\nWe believe that there are many, many others. Will\nyou help us by sending us the names and addresses of\nfriends who you think may be among their number?\nTHE WEEKLY REPUBLICAN,\nSpringfield, Mass.\nCoal Strike\u2019s Duration\nthe operators shall first accept \u201cin\nprinciple\u201d the welfare fund before\ndiscussing the most essential de\ntails.\nThe details are important be\ncause they involve the question\nwhether or not the union members\nshall have absolute control of the\nfund's administration and shall con\ntribute something from their wages\nio its upbuilding. The question of\nthe fund\u2019s administration year in\nand year out comes high in priority\nin collective bargaining, one would\nsay for coal consumers who must\npay the cost in higher prices. But\n[Mr Lewis won't discuss it until the\noperators first of all accept the fund\n|in principle. The general public\n[may develop a strong feeling that\n[a partial paralysis of the industrial\nsystem cannot he justified by\u2019 Mr\nLewis, or any\u2019one else, for the sake\nof winning his point of \"principle\u201d\nagainst the coal operators.\nMr Lewis has lost the public sup\nport of Mr Ickes, who has lately\nexpressed this very\u2019 strong senti\nment: \u201cSooner or later this country,\nif it has any pretense left to gov\nerning itself or possesses any dig\nnity, will smash John L. Lewis,\nwhile protecting the union in all of\nits rights.\u201d \u201cSmashing\u201d him in\nwhat sense? And how? Mr Ickes\nshould be more specific.\nMeantime, Mr Lewis is playing\nwith fire, so to speak. Mr Ickes is\nwithin the facts in pointing out\nthat \"coal is being pushed out of\nmarket after market by a rising\npetroleum and natural gas indus\ntry and the higher the miners push\nthe price of coal the greater the\nunemployment will be in the coal\nfields.\u201d\n(April UI\nWashington. But the British cabi\nnet system with its permanent un\ndersecretaries, which we lack, has\nseldom faced criticism of that sort.\nAs long as the war continued,*\nAlexandria was regarded as the\nbase which determined the fate of\nthe Suez canal. In the spring of\n1942, as the Germans under. Rom\nmel neared Alexandria in the drive\nwhich Montgomery finally stopped\nat El Alamein, it was accepted that\nif Alexandria fell control of the\ncanal would be lost and that what\nwas then left and movable of the\nBritish eastern Mediterranean fleet\nwould have to retreat through the\ncanal to the Indian ocean, leaving\nthe Germans in undisputed com\nmand. Now, however, it is declared\nthat the use of Alexandria was\nsolely a wartime measure in ac\ncordance with the Anglo-Egyptian\ntreaty.\nTwo explanations suggest them\nselves, one diplomatic and one mili\ntary. The evacuation of Alexan\ndria by the British may be a recog\nnition of the need, unwelcome but\nimperative, of bowing to Egyptian\nnationalism and putting the best\npossible face on the performance.\nIt may also be based on a recogni\ntion that the airplane has funda\nmentally changed the conditions\n\u25a0which govern the control of the\ncanal. This would involve a belief\nthat planes from Malta, that once\nhard-pressed fortress which the\nBritish retain, and from Cyprus,\nI which has large areas for airfields\n[although no port that could easily\nbe made a naval base, can command\n|an imperial lifeline through the\ncanal, which is no less important to\nBritain than it was before.\n[April 12]\nUnited States Senator Mead ap\npears to be leading as a potential\nDemocratic candidate for governor\nof New York, and former Gov Leh\nman is prominently mentioned for\nthe senatorship. Which raises again\nthe old question whether the gov\nernorship or the senatorship is the\nmore important\u2014and, incidentally,\nwhether the New York city mayor\nalty isn\u2019t more important than\neither.\nNational\nNo Peace in Europe\nSupreme Court Justice Jackson,\nthe chief American prosecutor at\nthe trial of the war criminals at\nNuernberg, Ger., sounded a rather\ngloomy note in his message to a\n\u201cforum\u201d in New York city.\nThere is nothing in Europe today,\nhe said, that can honestly be called\npeace. While military engagements\nhave ceased, the \u201cunderlying con\nflicts which set Europe fighting are\nnot solved,\u201d America has exhibited\nto Europe its might and skill in\ndestruction but \u201cit remains to be\nseen whether destructive capacity\nwill be the characteristic for which\nour country will be remembered.\u201d\nI Justice Jackson could have added\nthat hanging all the war criminals\nhe has been prosecuting will not\nsolve the \u201cunderlying conflicts which\nset Europe fighting.\u201d Even if the\ntrial should succeed in establish\ning new principles of international\njurisprudence, relative to personal\ncriminal responsibility for originat\ning and waging wars of aggression,\neven that achievement would be far\nshort of solving the war problem.\nThe foreign ministers of the big\nthree, who are to meet April 25,\nin Paris, in anxious search of solu\ntions of the peace-making problems\nof Italy and the Balkan states,\nwould welcome suggestions. But\nhanging Goering, Ribbentrop and all\nthe others for their abominable war\ncrimes would not help them in the\nleast.\nI April 15]\nThe Japanese at the Polls\nThe Japanese elections for a new\nParliament must have been carefully\nmanaged by\u2019 the Japanese. Gen Mac-\nArthur is satisfied. The Japanese\nwere credited long since with being\nhighly gifted as imitators. In these\nelections, their purpose was to imi\ntate western democracy, to Mac-\nArthur\u2019s satisfaction. That would\nalso shorten the American occupa\ntion of the country.\nTheir success is to be observed,\nfirst, in naming their most conserva\ntive parties, or groups, Liberals and\nProgressives. What\u2019s in a name?\nParticularly, the name of a polit\nical party. The more democratic\nparties in all European countries\nare nowadays called Socialist parties.\nIn France, if they are less Socialist\nthan the Socialists, they\u2019 are absurd\nly\u2019 called Radical Socialists. But\neverywhere, the Japanese must have\nobserved, there are Communist par\nties, too.\nThe new Japanese Parliament,\nconsequently, will have all the\ngroups which are found in our west\nern democracies, with much the\nsame party names. The Liberals\nlead in number of seats; the Pro\n[gressives come next; then the So\ncialists with at least 75 seats; and\ntrailing at the end of the proces\nsion are three Communists even.\nThe Japanese did not forget the Com\nmunists as an indispensable splin\nter group. And there is another evi-\nAmong the more fortunate de\nvelopments of the times may be\nlisted the submission to the House\nof Commons by Hugh Dalton, chan\ncellor of the exchequer in the Labor\ngovernment, of the British budget.\nIt has an importance for the United\nStates which no British budget has\nhad before. It comes on the eve\nof the debate in the Senate on the\nproposed loan to Great Britain.\nThe more nearly the British\nbudget is balanced, the more does\nthe British loan appear a sound and\ngood investment. Beyond the pros\npect that when, after an interim,\ninterest on the loan becomes due\nit will be paid and that the payment\nof the principal will follow in due\ncourse, the near approach to a bal\nance in the budget now before the\n[Commons is a hopeful sign of world\nprosperity in which the United\nStates will share.\nAn actual balancing of the Brit\nish budget is not contemplated in\nwhat the British call the fiscal year\n1946-47, but is in 1947-48. The\nmargin by which the present budget\nfalls short of balancing is appar\nently only 9 per cent, although\nthere are some discrepancies in the\nfigures given in the London dis\npatches. As announced to the\nCommons by Chancellor Dalton,\nBritish revenues during the coming\nyear will meet 91 per cent of the\noperating costs of government as\ncompared with 53 per cent in the\nlast year of the war.\nIt is worth recalling that the\nbudget which President Truman\nsent to Congress on January 21\ncalled for the estimated expendi\nture in our fiscal year beginning\nJuly 1 of \u201cjust above 35.8 billion,\u201d\nto quote Mr Truman\u2019s words. That\nsum the President expected to \u201cex\nceed estimated receipts by 4.3 bil\nlion dollars,\u201d the deficit to \u201cbe pro\nvided by a reduction in the cash\nbalance in the treasury\u201d without\nadditional borrowing. If the British\ndeficit is actually no more than 9\nper cent, they are relatively but\ndefinitely nearer a balance of cur\nrent receipts and expenditures than\nwe are with a budget more than\ntwice as big. Included in the Tru\nman estimate of receipts was\n$2,000,000,000 from the sale and\nrental of surplus property.\ndence of political modernity in the\nwestern democratic tradition \u2014near-\nly 40 women were elected to the\nnew Diet. \"What more do you\nwant?\u201d the Japanese may be say\ning, perhaps, to their conquerors.\nDown under the surface of the\npolitical trend, something happened\nquite as significant as anything re\nported. The heaviest vote in Japan\nwent to a virtual unknown \u2014Atsuo\nHirakawa, 38-year-old principal of a\nschool in the atom-bombed Hiro\nshima prefecture. He had 210,000\nsupporters. The heart of the Japa\nnese people is revealed in that vote\n\u2014which is something to remember.\n(April IM\nJail Scandal in Washington\nAs a result of the escape of two\ncondemned murderers, one recap\ntured and one still at large, from\nthe District of Columbia jail, an in\nvestigation has aLsdf--hu>ught out\nfacts hardly less sensational than\nthe escape itself, which was ac\ncomplished by first engaging two\njail attendants in a card game with\nthe two men awaiting execution.\nThe suspended superintendent of\nthe jail, who may, however, be sus\npected of a desire to involve others,\nhas charged that under his pre\ndecessor gross laxity prevailed and\nthat by the lavish use of tips pris\noners were able to \u201cthrow parties\u201d\nin jail for which liquor and women\nwere brought in. He has also de\nclared that the Engineers Group,\ninc., was organized and put into\noperation at the jail. It was be\ncause of his later connection with\nthis company that Mayor Curley of\nBoston, whose appeal is now pend\ning, was recently convicted in the\nfederal court in Washington with\ntwo other men.\n1 Whatever may be the accuracy of\nthe testimony of the suspended su\nperintendent on any one episode, it\nseems amply established that con\nditions in the jail were so lax as\nto be shocking. A further piece of\ntestimony was that prisoners, again\nby giving tips, were able to enjoy\nvisits to what has long been Wash\nington\u2019s most fashionable hotel.\nThis seems to be a charge which\ncan be quickly tested.\nPending further disclosures, it is\ndifficult to avoid the conclusion that\nthis episode furnishes one more in\ndictment of the way in which Wash\nington, its citizens deprived of the\nvote, is given a left-handed and in\neffectual government under the di\nrection of two congressional com\nmittees whose members, necessarily\nbusy on other matters, are neither\nelected nor qualified for such mu\nnicipal service. The chairman of\nthe Senate committee is none, other\nthan Senator Bilbo of Mississippi.\nI April 11 I\nThe South African village of\nNelsprint has a novel problem of\nceilings on buildings. A number of\nthree-room stone cottages, with\nmodern equipment, built for the na\ntives, are unoccupied, a spokesman\nfor the hoped-for tenants explain\ning: \u201cYou have made the ceilings\nof concrete in order that you may\ncause them to fall at your will and\nkill us.\u201d Our OPA\u2019s ceilings are\n[at least spared that sort of objec-\nI tion.\nThe British Budget\nThe British are realists. This\nbudget, presented by a Laborite\nchancellor who succeeds in that po\nsition a long line of statesmen\nwhose names are familiar in his\ntory, is evidence that in their de\ntermination to reestablish national\nsolvency and prosperity, the British\nare going about it in the only way\nin which, in the long run, it can be\naccomplished.\nThis budget is a confirmation of\nall that one learns, in gallant and\ncourageous letters from England, of\nthe manner in which the British\npeople, who stood alone as a bul\nwark against the menace of Nazism\nin the darkest days of the war, are\ncontinuing to draw their belts tight\n\u2014very tight indeed\u2014in order to\nassure their economic salvation as,\nwith our aid, they have already as\ni sured their political independence\nthrough victory in the war.\nWhen the Dalton budget is re\nferred to in London as \u201cconserva\ntive,\u201d the Labor chancellor is given\ncredit for facing the facts. While\nthe income and expenditures are\nnot yet quite balanced by the per\ncentage which has been referred\nto, Dalton has sturdily declared to\nthe Commons that thereafter \u201cthe\nchoice between having a budget sur\nplus and a budget deficit is in our\nown hands.\u201d The tone of that\nstatement indicates what the atti\ntude of Dalton and his Labor col\nleagues may be expected to prove.\nIt is clear that one factor in\nimpelling the British to retain so\nmuch of the wartime tax burden\nthe elimination of the excess prof\nits tax there, as here, being one of\nthe chief changes\u2014has been the de\nsire to create as favorable an im\npression as possible in Washington,\nwhere the British government is\nmore acutely aware than most\nAmericans that the debate on the\nBritish loan is about to begin.\nThe British would not be realists\nif they had not taken that factor\ninto consideration. But, having\ndone so, and having given what ap\npears to be predominantly favora\nble public approval to such a con\ntinuing tax burden, they are en\ntitled to the advantage it will bring\ni them.\n(April it!\nMassachusetts Scholars In\nCongress\nFormer Congressman Robert\nLuce, who for many years repre\nsented the old 13th, or Cambridge,\ndistrict in Washington and who re\ncently died, was second only to the\nelder Henry Cabot Lodge during\nthat time in upholding the Massa\nchusetts tradition of scholarship\namong our representatives .and\nsenators. Although Lodge was far\nmore widely known, Luce actually\ndid far more scholarly writing, as\nshown especially by the record of\nhis four volumes having to do with\ncongressional procedure and vari\nous congressional problems. In con\ntrast, Lodge's books, especially in\nlater years, were largely composed\nof collected addresses delivered on\nformal occasions, such as that on\nthe 150th anniversary, in 1903. of\nGreenfield\u2019s incorporation which\nlater gave to a book thc^tiHe, \u201c4\nFrontier Town and Other Essays.\u201d\nWhile Luce lacked Lodge\u2019s bril\nliance, he was painstaking and\nthorough. He was an especially\nhappy choice for the chairmanship\nof the committee of the House of\nRepresentatives which has charge in\nthat body of the affairs of our great\nnational library which, somewhat to\nits disadvantage through fostering\na misconception of its true role, is\nofficially known as the Library of\nCongress. In that capacity Robert\nLuce took his duties with complete\nseriousness and cooperated effec\ntively with Librarian Herbert Put\nnam, who had gone to Washington\nafter service in the Boston Public\nlibrary and under whom the Library\nof Congress had its great develop\nment into a national institution.\nOne of Luce\u2019s special interests\nis the Library of Congress was the\nexpansion of its collection of books\nprinted in braille for the blind and\navailable to them under a loan sys\ntem. In order to be sure that his\ncolleagues were ready to make the\nnecessary appropriations for this\nmost desirable purpose, he once in\nduced Miss Helen Keller to appear\nas a witness at a committee hear\ning, and a most effective witness\nshe made.\nAlthough it was from Congress\nthat the library took its name and\nfrom Congress that it got its funds,\nRobert Luce would have been the\nfirst to testify that, except for him\nself and too few other members of\nthe House and Senate, comparative\nly little use was made of it by\nthose who play the role of states-x\nmen at the Capitol and who, iff\nmost cases, would come nearer fill\ning that role if they read more and\nspoke less. But, however much or\nlittle the members of Congress\nmight use the library which, with\nall its vast stores of accumulated\nlearning, is supposed to be theirs,\nMr Luce saw in it the possibilities\nof a wider service to scholarship as\none of the great libraries of the\nworld.\nI April 111\nFake Conscription\nIf we are to have continued mili\ntary conscription, it should not be\na fake. The House has passed a\nbill extending the draft laws until\nFebruary 15, 1947, but the bill car\nries a provision preventing any\ndrafting prior to October 15. That\nlooks like a mockery, although it\nis said in justification that the spon\nsors of the hold-up wish to see vol\nunteering fully tested in the mean\ntime.\nThere is a much stronger jus\ntification for the bill\u2019s exemption of\nteen-age boys from the draft. When\nthe draft law was originally\u2019 en\nacted, it did not raid the high\nschools for 18 and 19-year-old lads.\nThey were brought within the draft\nbrackets after the army had felt the\nstrain of combat operations abroad.\nBut it seems so irrational as to\nI seem silly for Congress to extend\nthe draft for nine months and. at\nthe same time, prohibit inductions\nat any age for five months of that\nperiod.\nThe bill will eventually go before\na conference committee of the two\nbranches; the final product will\ndoubtless be a much better measure,\nfrom the army's standpoint, than\nthe one the House has passed. For\nthe Senate is probably less fearful\nof the political reaction at the polls\nnext November. The truth is, no\ndoubt, that any extension of the\nmilitary draft into the postwar pe\nriod is unpalatable to the Ameri\ncan people.\nf April IHJ\nThe through Pullman ears recent\nly provided for transcontinental pas\nsengers have been so rapidly booked\nin advance that only a relatively\nsmall number can be accommodated.\nThe three cars that the Santa Fe\nruns daily out of Los Angeles, for\ninstance, are solidly reserved\nthrough mid-May and beyond. Rail\nroad officials refer to the response\nas \u201cterrific,\u201d and apparently they\nmust either put on more through\ncars or travelers who cannot make\ntheir reservations far in advance\nwill be no better served than in\nthe past.\nA paper read before the Amer\nican Chemical society pictured pros\npects of a longer, healthier life for\nman as the result of the develop\nment of nucleic acid from yeast.\nEven with such a boasted elixir\navailable, however, it probably will\nbe advisable for longevity candi\ndates to be born with strong heart*\nand other first class organs, along\nwith a predisposition to modera\ntion!","height":"26114","width":"19428"}}
